          "content": "Let's take a journey back in time to learn about an interesting experiment conducted by a young researcher named Edward Deci at Carnegie Mellon University, about twenty years ago. Deci wanted to understand how rewards affect our motivation, especially when it comes to doing things we enjoy. To do this, he created a fun challenge for university students involving a puzzle called the Soma puzzle. This puzzle was not only engaging but also allowed the students to think creatively and solve problems.\nIn his experiment, Deci divided the students into two different groups. The first group was told that they would earn a small amount of money for each puzzle they solved. This meant that every time they completed a puzzle, they would receive a little cash as a reward. The second group, however, was asked to work on the puzzles without any payment at all. They were simply encouraged to enjoy the challenge and have fun with the puzzles.\nAfter the students had worked on the puzzles for several sessions, something interesting happened. The students who had been receiving money for their puzzle-solving efforts suddenly stopped getting paid. Deci and his research team carefully observed what happened next. They wanted to see if the students would continue to work on the puzzles in their free time, now that the money was no longer a factor.\nWhat they discovered was quite surprising! The students who had been paid began to show a significant decrease in their interest in solving puzzles once the money was gone. It seemed that the reward had changed how they viewed the activity. Instead of thinking, 'I enjoy this puzzle because it's fun and interesting,' they started to think, 'I only do this for the money.' When the money stopped, so did their motivation to engage with the puzzles.\nOn the other hand, the students who had never received any payment for their work continued to enjoy the puzzles just as much as they did at the beginning of the experiment. They remained curious and engaged, showing that their motivation came from their intrinsic interest in the puzzle itself, not from any external rewards.\nDeci's findings led him to an important conclusion: external rewards can sometimes take away our natural motivation. Instead of enhancing our interest in an activity, they can shift our focus to the reward itself. When the reward disappears, so can our desire to participate. This experiment teaches us a valuable lesson about motivation and the importance of doing things we love for the joy they bring us, rather than for external rewards.\nContext recap: Let's take a journey back in time to learn about an interesting experiment conducted by a young researcher named Edward Deci at Carnegie Mellon University, about twenty years ago. Deci wanted to understand how rewards affect our motivation, especially when it comes to doing things we enjoy. To do this, he created a fun challenge for university students involving a puzzle called the Soma puzzle. This puzzle was not only engaging but also allowed the students to think creatively and solve problems.\nWhy this matters: Deci's University Students and the Hidden Cost of Rewards helps learners in Business connect ideas from Drive: The Surprising Truth About What Motivates Us to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
